    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1956-04-30T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1956-04-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="315"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d315">
                <head>315. Letter From President <persName corresp="#p_EDD1" type="from"
                        >Eisenhower</persName> to Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_BGD1"
                        type="to">Ben Gurion</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d315fn1">Source: Department of State, <gloss
                            target="#t_SS1">S/S</gloss>–<gloss target="#t_NEA1">NEA</gloss> Files:
                        Lot 61 D 417, Omega #3.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1956-04-30">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 30, 1956</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. Prime Minister</hi>: I have delayed replying to
                    your important letter to me of March sixteenth<note n="2" xml:id="d315fn2">
                        <ref target="#d201">Document 201</ref>.</note> because of the rapid
                    developments that have been taking place, including notably the mission of
                    Secretary-General <persName corresp="#p_HD1">Hammarskjold</persName>. We are
                    awaiting his report with hope and confidence.</p>
                <p>The only reply I can give you at this moment to the chief subject of your letter,
                    the question of the sale of armaments, is a straightforward one. You have
                    presented your case forcefully and eloquently. But there are other factors to
                    which you do not allude, factors affecting the ability of the United States to
                    maintain its influence for peace in the area. We are not persuaded that it would
                    serve the cause of peace and stability in the world for the United States now to
                    accede to your request for arms sales. We continue to weigh the matter carefully
                    in the light of developments, and I may have occasion to communicate with you
                        further.<note n="3" xml:id="d315fn3">Telegram 822, May 1, transmitted the
                        text of the President’s letter to the Embassy in Tel Aviv and informed the
                        Embassy that the signed original had been delivered to the Israeli Embassy
                        the same day. (Department of State, Central Files, 396.1–PA/5–156)</note>
                </p>
                <p>With kindest personal regard and best wishes,</p>
                <p>Sincerely,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_EDD1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Dwight D. Eisenhower</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
